messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /users/forgot

All methods acceptable:
- false

Per-method acceptance (based on the code):
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: true
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation
- The main app mounts the user routes with app.use('/users', userRoutes) in index.js. That makes every route declared in routes/userRoutes.js be prefixed with /users.
- In routes/userRoutes.js the forgotPassword handler is registered as router.post('/forgot', forgotPassword). Combined with the mount prefix this yields the full path /users/forgot and the handler is registered for HTTP POST.
- There is no router.all(...) or any code that would indicate "all methods acceptable", so "All methods acceptable" is false.
- POST is true because the route is explicitly registered with router.post('/forgot', ...).
- OPTIONS is true because the application installs the cors() middleware globally (app.use(cors())). The cors middleware handles CORS preflight requests (OPTIONS) and will respond to OPTIONS requests, so OPTIONS is considered acceptable by the code.
- HEAD is false because there is no GET route at /users/forgot (Express only treats HEAD like GET when a GET route exists) and there is no explicit HEAD handler.
- TRACE is false (no handler or middleware enabling TRACE).
- GET, PUT, DELETE, PATCH are all false because there are no route handlers for those methods on /users/forgot.
